    # [Scene: Community Rooftop Garden | Early Evening — Several Months Later]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, sustaining chord — tempered by a minor string undercurrent]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft murmur of conversation; distant surf; the creak of a rain barrel settling]
    "You remember the night you hit 'publish' — the protocol spread across the town like an open window. Maps, watering regimens, volunteer rosters; the whole thing, raw and stitched and free. For a while the world"
    "answered. Rooftop beds bristled with seedlings. Elders in oilskins came back to tend eelgrass plots as if recognizing a long-lost kin. Fishermen traded once-secret tips for anchor points and seedling months. The waterline, ridiculous and slow,"
    "hesitated in a place you could point to and say, 'Look.'"
    "You sit on the low wall beside Ilias. His jacket smells faintly of kelp and dryer lint from a night sampling at the breakwater. His camera rests against his thigh, lens cap off like an eye"
    "attentive to everything. When he smiles at you, it doubles in the crinkling at his eyes — a small, human geography you could memorize."
    show ilias_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilias_navarro "You did something the town needed. You made it possible for people to try without waiting for permission."
    show maya_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kestrel "We made it possible. Volunteers stayed up longer than they should have. Etta braided the scheduling like a net."

    ilias_navarro "Her nets are better than municipal timetables."

    maya_kestrel "She'd say the same thing about your data sheets if you weren't so earnest about plotting contour lines."

    ilias_navarro "Your notebook? It's a poor thing to hold against the sea. But it gave people a place to start."
    "You feel the usual swell — pride braided with that old, sharp guilt. You think of the ledger, of all the names that might have been written in different ink if you had acted sooner."

    maya_kestrel "We did start. Sometimes that's the most honest thing to do."
    "Ilias Navarro watches you, ocean-blue eyes leveled and steady. There is a modest, earnest pride in him that makes your chest ache with something both warm and fragile."

    ilias_navarro "Promise me... small things. A picnic on the High Tide Boardwalk when the spring storms hold off. Teach me to patch a floor so I don't scrape my knees on your boat when I'm clumsy with timber."
    "You picture a picnic blanket flapping at the edge of the boardwalk, thermoses and sandwiches, the town in soft focus. You imagine mending a floor together, mud and laughter and taut rope."

    maya_kestrel "A picnic. And I'll teach you the stubborn way to nail oak — not because it holds better, but because it remembers."

    ilias_navarro "That's all I need."

    menu:
        "Trace the map with him, planning the picnic route":
            "You lean over the notebook and trace the path with your finger, naming alleys and hidden benches. The planning steadies both of you; the world narrows to an ink line and the promise of a simple afternoon."
        "Take his hand, wordless":
            "Your fingers find his and hold on without a script. The warmth is small and immediate; you both laugh as if to break a pressure that's been holding the town all week."

